		<atom10:link xmlns:atom10="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml" href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/realscience/posts" /><feedburner:info uri="realscience/posts" /><atom10:link xmlns:atom10="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" rel="hub" href="http://pubsubhubbub.appspot.com/" /><item>
		<title>Asteroid Barrage Calls for Citizen Science Spotters</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/mS3jUfZ03cE/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/06/06/asteroid-barrage-calls-for-citizen-science-spotters/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 06 Jun 2012 19:49:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Astronomy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Backyard Science]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Citizen science]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Consumer Safety]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Discoveries]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Space]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7176</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
Potentially hazardous asteroids (PHAs) are orbiting space rocks that come within five million miles of Earth. As you can imagine, there are a lot of asteroids that qualify as regionally or globally dangerous.
And two sizable asteroids narrowly missed Earth at the end of May, one zipping less than 10,000 miles away from us. 
A 16-foot [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe frameborder="0" scrolling="no" src="http://eplayer.clipsyndicate.com/embed/iframe?pf_id=1&#038;show_title=0&#038;va_id=3502949&#038;windows=1" width="425" height="330"></iframe></p>
<p>Potentially hazardous asteroids (PHAs) are orbiting space rocks that come within five million miles of Earth. As you can imagine, there are a lot of asteroids that qualify as regionally or globally dangerous.</p>
<p>And two sizable asteroids narrowly missed Earth at the end of May, one zipping less than 10,000 miles away from us. <div id="attachment_7178" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/AsteroidinfrontofEarth.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/AsteroidinfrontofEarth-e1339011014357.jpg" alt="Small Asteroid Zips by Earth, May 30, 2012" title="AsteroidinfrontofEarth" width="325" height="220" class="size-full wp-image-7178" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Small Asteroid Zips by Earth, May 30, 2012</p></div></p>
<p>A 16-foot asteroid discovered on Memorial Day whizzed past Earth just 8,950 miles from Earth&#8217;s surface. That&#8217;s a very close call. NASA&#8217;s Jet Propulsion Laboratory, which tracks such flybys, said the asteroid — dubbed <a href="http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2012%20KT42;orb=0;cov=0;log=0;cad=0#orb">2012 KT42</a> — was the sixth closest asteroid approach.</p>
<p>And it was the second asteroid encounter during the last week of May. On May 28, another asteroid, measuring 69 feet across, flew by at a distance of 32,000 miles.</p>
<p>Because these dark-colored space rocks appear inky black against the darkness of space, it is very difficult to spot an asteroid until it gets really close to Earth or until the sun shines on it to reveal its size and shape. Unfortunately, those are the space rocks that stand a greater chance of crashing into Earth.</p>
<p>The good news is that a direct collision happens about twice every million years. So it&#8217;s rather unlikely that anyone living today will experience an asteroid hitting Earth. But there are some long-range projections of big asteroids that regularly intersect Earth&#8217;s orbit that will squeak by, much like the two asteroids that buzzed us at the end of May.</p>
<p>NASA has its <a href="http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/">Near Earth Objects office</a> that monitors asteroids, including PHAs that threaten Earth. Telescope operators located in Hawaii and a couple of other places point powerful telescopes at suspect objects, including NEOs as requested by NASA and the European Space Agency.</p>
<p>Because the sky is a big place and professional astronomers are far outnumbered by potential objects in space, NASA is enlisting the help of amateur astronomers and citizen scientists to help sift through mountains of data, identify NEOs and even act as an early warning system for asteroids that have their sights set on Earth.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7179" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/NEAs.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/NEAs-e1339011544655.jpg" alt="An Edge-On View of the Solar System. Dots Represent the Population of NEAs and PHAs That Scientists Think Exist Based on the NEOWISE Survey" title="NEAs" width="325" height="243" class="size-full wp-image-7179" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">An Edge-On View of the Solar System. Dots Represent the Population of NEAs and PHAs That Scientists Think Exist Based on the NEOWISE Survey</p></div>Earlier this spring, NASA announced <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/home/hqnews/2012/apr/HQ12-121_OSIRIS-REx_Outreach_NEOs.html">Target Asteroids!</a>, a new citizen science project designed to support NASA&#8217;s <a href="http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/">Origins Spectral Interpretation Resource Identification Security &#8211; Regolith Explorer</a> (OSIRIS-REx) mission scheduled for launch in 2016 that will study material from an asteroid.</p>
<p>Scientists haven&#8217;t been to the different types of asteroids to take geological samples to determine their composition. So much about asteroids, including successful ways to move them out of the way, remain a mystery.</p>
<p>NASA hopes that its new program will excite people about space and science and allow them to participate in a project to classify the population of NEOs, their position, motion, rotation and changes in the intensity of light they emit.</p>
<p><a href="http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/targetasteroids.html">Target Asteroids!</a> data will be useful for comparisons with actual mission data. Then professional astronomers can use this refine theoretical models of asteroids and improve their understanding of asteroids similar to the one OSIRIS-Rex will encounter in 2019, designated 1999 RQ36.</p>
<p>OSIRIS-Rex project scientist Jason Dworkin at NASAs Goddard Space Flight Center says, &#8220;Although few amateur astronomers have the capability to observe 1999 RQ36 itself, they do have the capability to observe other targets.&#8221;</p>
<p>And getting better acquainted with asteroids, what they are made of and how they travel will help astronomers select destinations for manned missions to asteroids &#8212; like the one planned for planetoid Vesta. </p>
<p>And ESA is enlisting the power of crowdsourcing to help collect observations about PHAs as part of Europe’s contribution to the global asteroid hunt.</p>
<p>A new project in conjunction with the <a href="http://www.faulkes-telescope.com/">UK’s Faulkes Telescope Project</a> will set students loose tracking NEOs and watching for hazardous asteroids.</p>
<p>ESA’s Space Situational Awareness (SSA) program keeps watch over space hazards, including disruptive space weather, debris objects in Earth orbit and asteroids that pass close enough to cause concern.  </p>
<p>Professional research projects often turn to the armies of amateur astronomers around the world to help with observations or to lend a hand with the vast amounts of data that need processing. And it&#8217;s thanks to initiatives like Faulkes that makes research-grade instruments available that make projects like this viable.</p>
<p>Detlef Koschny, the head of NEO activity at ESAs SSA program office says, &#8220;The wider astronomy community offers a wealth of expertise and enthusiasm, and they have the time and patience to verify new sightings; this helps tremendously.&#8221; </p>
<p>While the Faulkes project focuses on schools, amateurs will be able to freely access the project&#8217;s data archives. ESAs archives are also open to all, and they work with amateur astronomers with the Teide Observatory Tenerife Asteroid Survey (TOTAS) team, who use a 1-meter telescope at the ESAs Optical Ground Station on Tenerife in the Canary Islands. Since starting their SSA-sponsored survey work in January 2010, the TOTAS amateur astronomers have identified hundreds of asteroid candidates, over 20 of which have been confirmed and named.<div id="attachment_7180" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 308px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/NewComet.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/NewComet-e1339011924401.jpg" alt="School Children in Northern Ireland Discover New Comet, Only 5AU from Earth, February 2012" title="NewComet" width="298" height="300" class="size-full wp-image-7180" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">School Children in Northern Ireland Discover New Comet, Only 5AU from Earth, February 2012</p></div></p>
<p>And grade school students in Northern Ireland who were studying the positions of six NEOs, identified a never-before-seen comet, for which they received a special mention in a <a href="http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/services/MPEC.html">Minor Planet Electronic Circular</a>, an electronic bulletin reporting urgent results of Near Earth Objects sent out to the astronomical community.</p>
<p>Nick Howes, Pro-Am Programme Manager at the Faulkes Telescope says, &#8220;For European students, collaborating on exciting ESA activities and possibly detecting new NEOs is very appealing, as it&#8217;s engagement with one of the world&#8217;s great space agencies doing critical scientific work.&#8221;</p>
<p>And getting as many eyes on the sky as we can is the best way to identify all potential asteroid threats. Citizen science is probably the best way to accomplish that.</p>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F06%2F06%2Fasteroid-barrage-calls-for-citizen-science-spotters%2F&amp;title=Asteroid%20Barrage%20Calls%20for%20Citizen%20Science%20Spotters" id="wpa2a_2"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
