		<item>
		<title>Radioactive Tuna Makes Trek from Japan to U.S.</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/j8Zumb4U7rE/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/06/04/radioactive-tuna-makes-trek-from-japan-to-u-s/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 04 Jun 2012 18:47:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Animals]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Consumer Safety]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Food and Nutrition]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Health and Medicine]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Japanese Tsunami]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Marine Science]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7151</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
For the first time ever scientists were able to use the nuclear disaster in Japan to track the migration of fish. After finding bluefin tuna with high levels of two cesium radioisotopes, marine biologists were able to determine the migration route for the species between Japan and California.
Scientists say they are surprised to see that [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe frameborder="0" scrolling="no" src="http://eplayer.clipsyndicate.com/embed/iframe?pf_id=1&#038;show_title=0&#038;va_id=3526056&#038;windows=1" width="425" height="330"></iframe></p>
<p>For the first time ever scientists were able to use the nuclear disaster in Japan to track the migration of fish. After finding bluefin tuna with high levels of two cesium radioisotopes, marine biologists were able to determine the migration route for the species between Japan and California.</p>
<p>Scientists say they are surprised to see that blue fin tuna that were swimming near Japan last year during the nation&#8217;s nuclear crisis following a massive earthquake and tsunami still show signs of radioactivity after migrating all the way to the coast of California some 6,000 miles away.</p>
<p>After taking routine samples of the popular food fish off the coast of California, marine biologists found that all the fish tested contain levels of two radioactive isotopes &#8212; Cesium-134 and Cesium-137. <div id="attachment_7153" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/BluefinTuna.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/BluefinTuna-e1338835110245.jpg" alt="Bluefin Tuna Make 6,000-Mile Migratory Trek Carrying Japanese Radiation" title="BluefinTuna" width="325" height="246" class="size-full wp-image-7153" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Bluefin Tuna Make 6,000-Mile Migratory Trek Carrying Japanese Radiation</p></div></p>
<p><a href="http://www.somas.stonybrook.edu/people/fisher.html">Nicholas Fisher</a> from Stony Brook University in New York was shocked that every blue fin tuna his team analyzed still had measurable levels of radioactivity. Results from the study are published in the May 29 issue of <em><a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2012/05/22/1204859109.full.pdf+html?sid=cc8ae292-2761-4ed9-b0f3-e8f82de97bcb">Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the U.S.</a></em> </p>
<p>Stanford University marine biology PhD candidate <a href="http://micheli.stanford.edu/DanielMadigan.html">Daniel Madigan</a> is studying migration of large predators like sharks and bluefin tuna. While he was surprised that the tuna the team tested had elevated Cesium levels, he is more surprised that no one else is studying other marine animals that were likely affected by high radiation levels following the Fukushima Dai-Chi nuclear crisis.</p>
<p>He says, &#8220;We were surprised to find this radioactivity in all bluefin tested, but we were also surprised that, to our knowledge, no other animals far from Japan have been tested.&#8221;</p>
<p>While the bluefin found near San Diego last August contain some extra radiation, the amounts are still within the safe range for human consumption. </p>
<div id="attachment_7154" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 570px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/BluefinTunaRadiationMap.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/BluefinTunaRadiationMap-e1338835216870.jpg" alt="Bluefin Tuna Migration Route between Japan and California, March and August 2011" title="BluefinTunaRadiationMap" width="560" height="189" class="size-full wp-image-7154" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Bluefin Tuna Migration Route between Japan and California, March and August 2011</p></div>
<p><a href="http://www.montereybayaquarium.org/cr/seafoodwatch.aspx?c=dd">Seafood Watch</a> scientist Tom Pickerell says that given the scale of the incident in Japan he isn&#8217;t surprised that fish picked up radioactivity and have absorbed it into their muscle tissue.</p>
<p>Scientists will monitor radioactivity levels in tuna and other food fish for years to come. Madigan says the discovery proves unequivocally the timing and migration routes of bluefin tuna. </p>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F06%2F04%2Fradioactive-tuna-makes-trek-from-japan-to-u-s%2F&amp;title=Radioactive%20Tuna%20Makes%20Trek%20from%20Japan%20to%20U.S." id="wpa2a_6"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/GH2VKd3sk0Y28xQghz5PWO3_hRU/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/GH2VKd3sk0Y28xQghz5PWO3_hRU/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/GH2VKd3sk0Y28xQghz5PWO3_hRU/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/GH2VKd3sk0Y28xQghz5PWO3_hRU/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:l6gmwiTKsz0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=l6gmwiTKsz0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:7Q72WNTAKBA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=7Q72WNTAKBA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:dnMXMwOfBR0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=dnMXMwOfBR0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:-BTjWOF_DHI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=j8Zumb4U7rE:HDd0tlEPolQ:-BTjWOF_DHI" border="0"></img></a>
</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/realscience/posts/~4/j8Zumb4U7rE" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
