		<item>
		<title>Dragon Completes First Private Space Mission with Splash Down</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/HeSmTOl5UPY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/31/dragon-completes-first-private-space-mission-with-splash-down/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 31 May 2012 18:46:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Space]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7143</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
Though the Dragon space capsule returned safely in a splash down 400 miles off the coast of California the mission was deemed a success just after launch on May 22. And each milestone it reached along the 9-day journey was met as another victory for the first private space cargo supply capsule.
Even before unberthing from [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe frameborder="0" scrolling="no" src="http://eplayer.clipsyndicate.com/embed/iframe?pf_id=1&#038;show_title=0&#038;va_id=3528990&#038;windows=1" width="425" height="330"></iframe></p>
<p>Though the Dragon space capsule returned safely in a splash down 400 miles off the coast of California the mission was deemed a success just after launch on May 22. And each milestone it reached along the 9-day journey was met as another victory for the first private space cargo supply capsule.</p>
<p>Even before unberthing from the International Space Station, Dragon mission director John Couluris says, &#8220;It was a major success for us.&#8221; After spending five days attached to the orbiting space lab Dragon disconnected and began its return trip. After a ten-minute engine burn the capsule began its fiery reentry into Earth&#8217;s atmosphere.</p>
<p>After the red and white parachutes were spotted from planes circling the landing zone, a triumphant SpaceX CEO tweeted, &#8220;Splashdown successfull!!&#8221; Those words from and elated Elon Musk.</p>
<p>Unlike other vehicles Dragon is built to withstand a super-heated reentry, capable of withstanding temperatures above 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit. And on its first return trip, the capsule is carrying old equipment, science experiments and other payload that will be sent to NASA once it is recovered and returned to SpaceX headquarters in Hawthorne, CA, outside of Los Angeles.</p>
<p>This successful test flight proves that the era of commercial space flight has arrived. The entire mission unfolded without a hitch.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7144" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DragonCapsuleSplashdown-e1338489714999.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DragonCapsuleSplashdown-e1338489714999.jpg" alt="Dragon Capsule Floats in Pacific, Waiting Recovery Ships, photo by Mike Altenhofen/SpaceX" title="DragonCapsuleSplashdown" width="325" height="214" class="size-full wp-image-7144" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Dragon Capsule Floats in Pacific, Waiting Recovery Ships, photo by Mike Altenhofen/SpaceX</p></div>For now, Dragon is the only capsule capable of delivering and returning cargo from the International Space Station. But several other private companies are hoping to secure contracts with NASA for future trips to the low-orbit space outpost. Besides SpaceX, three companies &#8212; Sierra Nevada Corp., Boeing, and Blue Origin &#8212; are working on capsules to take astronauts to and from the space station.</p>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F05%2F31%2Fdragon-completes-first-private-space-mission-with-splash-down%2F&amp;title=Dragon%20Completes%20First%20Private%20Space%20Mission%20with%20Splash%20Down" id="wpa2a_8"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/g2OWhXBtVr6-WKHeiJJbG56LXJM/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/g2OWhXBtVr6-WKHeiJJbG56LXJM/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/g2OWhXBtVr6-WKHeiJJbG56LXJM/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/g2OWhXBtVr6-WKHeiJJbG56LXJM/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:l6gmwiTKsz0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=l6gmwiTKsz0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:7Q72WNTAKBA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=7Q72WNTAKBA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:dnMXMwOfBR0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=dnMXMwOfBR0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:-BTjWOF_DHI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=HeSmTOl5UPY:00Jw8TIK-_4:-BTjWOF_DHI" border="0"></img></a>
</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/realscience/posts/~4/HeSmTOl5UPY" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/31/dragon-completes-first-private-space-mission-with-splash-down/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
