		<item>
		<title>Dragon Launch Ushers in Entrepreneurial Era in Space</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/WE5HaHbESP0/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/22/dragon-launch-ushers-in-entrepreneurial-era-in-space/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 22 May 2012 20:43:40 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Space]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7133</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
Billionaire tech mogul Elon Musk oversaw the launch of his latest enterprise from his own mission control in California while in Florida his t-shirt and shorts clad team took over the control center at Cape Canaveral. When the Dragon rocket ignited and lifted off effortlessly into the Florida predawn sky, a new era of space [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe frameborder="0" scrolling="no" src="http://eplayer.clipsyndicate.com/embed/iframe?pf_id=1&#038;show_title=0&#038;va_id=3510301&#038;windows=1" width="425" height="330"></iframe></p>
<p>Billionaire tech mogul <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elon_Musk">Elon Musk</a> oversaw the launch of his latest enterprise from his own mission control in California while in Florida his t-shirt and shorts clad team took over the control center at Cape Canaveral. When the Dragon rocket ignited and lifted off effortlessly into the Florida predawn sky, a new era of space exploration officially began.</p>
<p>Musk&#8217;s company <a href="http://www.spacex.com">SpaceX </a>has spent over $1 billion and ten year working to become NASA&#8217;s taxi, ferrying astronauts to and from the International Space Station. Today&#8217;s launch was the audition for that job, which won&#8217;t begin for another three years. But successful liftoff with payload &#8212; mostly food and supplies &#8212; proves that a commercial entity can augment a government space program.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7137" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 372px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DragonLaunchT+05.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DragonLaunchT+05.jpg" alt="SpaceX Launches New Era with Successful Liftoff of Falcon 9 Rocket and Dragon Launch Vehicle, May 22, 2012" title="DragonLaunchT+05" width="362" height="593" class="size-full wp-image-7137" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">SpaceX Launches New Era with Successful Liftoff of Falcon 9 Rocket and Dragon Launch Vehicle, May 22, 2012</p></div>On Twitter proud papa Musk says, &#8220;Feels like a giant weight just came off my back.&#8221; Later he tells reporters, &#8220;For us, it&#8217;s like winning the Super Bowl.&#8221;</p>
<p>And this test flight had a lot riding on it. After several scrubbed attempts late last year and a last second abort last Saturday, a successful launch means that the commercial space age is finally here. Even Musk&#8217;s competitors are pleased by the first-stage success.</p>
<p>Mark Sirangelo, the chairman of <a href="http://www.sncorp.com/snc_ss.php">Sierra Nevada Corp. Space Systems</a> says, &#8220;The shuttle may be retired, but the American dream of space exploration is alive and well.&#8221;</p>
<p>NASA Administrator <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_F._Bolden,_Jr.">Charles Bolden</a> seemed to proudly hand over the keys of low-Earth orbit space travel to private companies. He says, &#8220;The significance of this day cannot be overstated.&#8221; He says it&#8217;s a great day for America and for the world because there were those out there who thought that once the 30-year-old space shuttle program was retired last year that the U.S. was no longer in the space business.</p>
<p>And until today space was purely the domain of governments so that assumption was not so off base. But in the last ten years dozens of space companies have been designing crew vehicles, rockets, elevators and space planes. Several companies, including SpaceX secured lucrative contracts from NASA to do some of the heavy lifting that the shuttles used to do.</p>
<p>Because today&#8217;s launch was considered a test flight, the Falcon 9 rocket with unmanned Dragon crew vehicle attached to the tip is only carrying non-essential items just in case something went wrong. Just before 4:00 a.m. EDT the rocket launched without a hitch and began its three day journey to meet up with the ISS.</p>
<p>Only five different vehicles have rendezvoused with the orbiting space station and so far they have all been governments. On Saturday, if all continues to go well, the Dragon  will become the first commercial launch vehicle to dock at a space outpost.</p>
<p>President Obama&#8217;s science adviser John Holdren says of the occasion, &#8220;This expanded role for the private sector will free up more of NASA&#8217;s resources to do what NASA does best &#8212; tackle the most demanding technological challenges in space, including those of human spaceflight beyond low-Earth orbit.&#8221;</p>
<p>As the rocket raced into the night sky, the controllers on the ground celebrated. They cheered when the Dragon reached orbit, nine minutes into its flight. And they embraced once the solar panels opened as planned. The next milestone moment in this flight will occur on Thursday when the Dragon gets close to the space station. From over a mile away it will practice docking maneuvers. And if all goes well the actual docking will take place on Friday.</p>
<p>The six-crew team aboard the ISS will be happy to receive 1,000 pounds of groceries and other goodies from home. The Dragon is also carrying a special payload &#8212; the ashes of 300 people (including the actor who played Scotty in the Star Trek TV series.) The company <a href="http://www.celestis.com/">Celestis </a>sends the cremated remains of loved ones to orbit eternally aboard key rocket launches. </p>
<p>After a week attached to the station the capsule will begin its return trip in about a week. It won&#8217;t return empty though. It is scheduled to return science experiments and equipment. Unlike other vehicles that burn up on the way back through the atmosphere, the Dragon will splash down in the Pacific.</p>
<p>Regardless of what happens in the next week, two more Dragon launches are planned this year. And the private space race has begun.</p>
<p>Musk says, &#8220;This mission heralds the dawn of a new era of space exploration, one in which there is a significant commercial space element. It is like the advent of the Internet in the mid-1990s when commercial companies entered what was originally a government endeavor. That move dramatically accelerated the pace of advancement and made the Internet accessible to the mass market. I think we’re at a similar inflection point for space. I hope and I believe that this mission will be historic in marking that turning point towards a rapid advancement in space transportation technology.&#8221;</p>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F05%2F22%2Fdragon-launch-ushers-in-entrepreneurial-era-in-space%2F&amp;title=Dragon%20Launch%20Ushers%20in%20Entrepreneurial%20Era%20in%20Space" id="wpa2a_10"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XPh_R4mx3TQS8E28Q2zTIvf0RN0/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XPh_R4mx3TQS8E28Q2zTIvf0RN0/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XPh_R4mx3TQS8E28Q2zTIvf0RN0/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XPh_R4mx3TQS8E28Q2zTIvf0RN0/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:l6gmwiTKsz0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=l6gmwiTKsz0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:7Q72WNTAKBA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=7Q72WNTAKBA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:dnMXMwOfBR0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=dnMXMwOfBR0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:-BTjWOF_DHI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=WE5HaHbESP0:GCDhKbNzLNk:-BTjWOF_DHI" border="0"></img></a>
</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/realscience/posts/~4/WE5HaHbESP0" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/22/dragon-launch-ushers-in-entrepreneurial-era-in-space/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
