		<item>
		<title>Three in South Battle Flesh-Eating Bacteria</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/FEpIVSMhBYM/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/21/three-in-south-battle-flesh-eating-bacteria/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 21 May 2012 18:52:02 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Biology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Consumer Safety]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Diseases]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Health and Medicine]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7103</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
24-year old Aimee Copeland was the picture of health. She was working towards a Masters degree in psychology at the University of West Georgia before she went zip-lining three weeks ago. During a weekend trip the adventurous student fell off a zip-line when it broke, cut herself and landed in a rocky river where a [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/UljFaOXIfSU?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>24-year old <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/news/aimee-copeland">Aimee Copeland</a> was the picture of health. She was working towards a Masters degree in psychology at the University of West Georgia before she went zip-lining three weeks ago. During a weekend trip the adventurous student fell off a zip-line when it broke, cut herself and landed in a rocky river where a common bacteria got into the wound and began eating away at her soft tissue. Doctors think that a particularly virulent form of a waterborne bacteria caused Copeland&#8217;s infection.</p>
<p>Called <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmedhealth/PMH0002415/">necrotizing fasciitis</a>, this life-threatening condition can be started by any number of common bacteria. In this case Copeland was exposed to a very aggressive form of <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeromonas_hydrophila">Aeromonas hydrophila</a></em>. The problem arises when that bacteria gets into a deep wound like the one Copeland sustained on her thigh requiring 22 stitches on May 1 after a homemade zip-line broke. <div id="attachment_7110" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 202px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/AimeeCopeland.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/AimeeCopeland-e1337711245292.jpg" alt="Aimee Copeland, 24-Year-Old Georgia Graduate Student " title="AimeeCopeland" width="192" height="250" class="size-full wp-image-7110" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Aimee Copeland, 24-Year-Old Georgia Graduate Student </p></div></p>
<p>After a number of surgeries Copeland had to have both hands and feet amputated as well as part of her abdomen so doctors could get ahead of the infection, which can be treated with antibiotics if caught early enough. But in Copeland&#8217;s case the infection was very deep, causing her a lot of pain, but didn&#8217;t appear unusual by looking at the stitched wound.</p>
<p>It took doctors four days to determine the infection and by that time the flesh eating was already underway. To prevent the infection from jumping from the soft tissue to the blood stream where it would cause sepsis doctors have to amputate the dead tissue.</p>
<p>One in five cases of flesh-eating bacterial infections result in death. Copeland is bucking the odds after doctors gave her a grim prognosis two weeks ago. She is off the ventilator and breathing on her own but she isn&#8217;t out of the woods yet.</p>
<p>A new mom and a landscaper also have contracted flesh-eating bacterial infections in Georgia this month. While the infections are very rare &#8212; occurring in only about 750 people each year &#8212; warm ponds and rivers are play host to the very bacteria that can destroy the soft tissue. It&#8217;s really the person&#8217;s immune system that determines how severe the infection will be.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7111" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 218px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LanaKuykendall.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LanaKuykendall-e1337711410655.jpg" alt="Lana Kukendall, 36-Year-Old South Carolina New Mom and Paramedic" title="LanaKuykendall" width="208" height="250" class="size-full wp-image-7111" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Lana Kukendall, 36-Year-Old South Carolina New Mom and Paramedic</p></div>In the case of 36-year-old <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/21/lana-kuykendall-flesh-eating-bacteria-necrotizing-fasciitis_n_1531665.html">Lana Kuykendall</a> her immune system was naturally compromised because she was in the third trimester of her pregnancy with her twins. Shortly after delivering them in Atlanta, she returned to Greenville, South Carolina where the new mom who is also a paramedic went to the hospital after becoming worried about a bruise that appeared to be growing on the back of her leg. By the time she got to the emergency room it had grown to the size of a sheet of paper. And by the time they wheeled her into the operating room it had eaten a significant chunk of her legs.</p>
<p>Kuykendall had had seven surgeries to remove the bacteria-ravaged tissue. Doctors think that she contracted streptococcus, the same bacteria that causes sore throats and acne. But she and Copeland aren&#8217;t alone. <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/21/bobby-vaughn-flesh-eating-bacteria-necrotizing-fasciitis_n_1533806.html">Bobby Vaughn</a>, a 32 year old landscaper in Cartersville, Georgia had a similar flesh-eating infection that went from the size of a peanut to a grapefruit in no time, he told a local TV station.</p>
<p>South Carolina state epidemiologist <a href="http://www.sph.sc.edu/epid_bios/facultystaffdetails.php?ID=339">Jerry Gibson</a> says that Group A streptococcus lives on people&#8217;s skin or in their nose but generally remains harmless. He says infection can be triggered by &#8220;something subtle, sometimes in a person who has poor nutrition or alcohol use, but also in people who have no immune deficiencies.&#8221;</p>
<p>Microbiologist <a href="http://medschool.umaryland.edu/facultyresearchprofile/viewprofile.aspx?id=2155">Amy Horneman</a>, the director of microbiology and molecular diagnostics at the Maryland Veteran&#8217;s Affairs isn&#8217;t involved in any of the current flesh-eating bacteria cases but she says the bacteria themselves are very common. <div id="attachment_7115" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 283px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Aeromonas_hydrophila.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Aeromonas_hydrophila.jpg" alt="Aeromonas hydrophilia, Rod-Shaped Bacteria under a Microscope" title="Aeromonas_hydrophila" width="273" height="220" class="size-full wp-image-7115" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Aeromonas hydrophilia, Rod-Shaped Bacteria under a Microscope</p></div></p>
<p>She says the water-loving variety of the microorganism Aeromonas is found in freshwater sources such as lakes, ponds, rivers and streams, as well as brackish water like the Chesapeake Bay and Puget Sound. They can also be found in drinking and surface waters, especially recreational sources. Of the 33 strains of the bacteria only eight are known to cause problems in people. Those problems include diarrhea, wound infections, respiratory, ocular, and bloodstream infections. Dr. Horneman says some other serious but less common infections caused by this organism include necrotizing fasciitis and kidney failure.</p>
<p>The bacteria is more common during the warmer months from April to October and infections generally coincide with recreational water activities like swimming, fishing or boating. People can become sick by either ingesting the bacteria or by exposing an open cut to the bacteria in the water.</p>
<p>Dr. Horneman says that people with compromised immune systems are more at risk but that healthy people like Copeland are also subject to infection.</p>
<p>A Georgia TV station wanted to know what was in the water after Copeland&#8217;s story became public. A reporter took samples from the Little Tallapoosa River, where Copeland landed after the zip-line broke. She took the water to Emory University to have it analyzed and found that there were about 140 A. hydrophilia bacteria cells per tablespoon of water. Those findings aren&#8217;t terribly surprising and nothing to be overtly worried about.</p>
<p>Scientists at Emory&#8217;s <a href="http://www.sph.emory.edu/CGSW/">Center for Global Safe Water</a> say the concentration of bacteria in untreated water &#8212; like lakes and rivers &#8212; can change on a daily basis. Certainly 140 cells per mL is measurable but nowhere near the high of harmful bacteria 10,000 cells per mL that those researchers have reported in the past.</p>
<p>Dr. Amy Kirby tested the river water samples and says, &#8220;Aeromonas and streptococcus are very ubiquitous bacteria so you are going to be exposed to it every day.&#8221; But she says, &#8220;It&#8217;s just a matter of getting more dangerous exposures.&#8221; <div id="attachment_7113" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 267px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/BobbyVaughn.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/BobbyVaughn-e1337711567359.jpg" alt="Bobby Vaughn, 32-Year-Old Georgia Landscaper" title="BobbyVaughn" width="257" height="250" class="size-full wp-image-7113" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Bobby Vaughn, 32-Year-Old Georgia Landscaper</p></div></p>
<p>Vaughn fell out of a tree and cut his side, leading to one of those more dangerous exposures. He began feeling sick right away. He tells <a href="http://www.cbsatlanta.com/story/18558629/catersville-man-fighting-off-flesh-eating-bacteria">CBS News</a>, &#8220;I just out of the blue wasn&#8217;t feeling real well, and I went over and sat in my truck for a minute, and I was feeling real hot, and I started vomiting, you know, so we just stopped for the day.&#8221;</p>
<p>He tells the <a href="http://www2.nbc26.tv/news/2012/may/21/georgia-man-suffering-flesh-eating-bacteria-being--ar-3830509/">NBC affiliate in Atlanta</a> learning about what both Kuyrkendal and Copeland are facing makes what he&#8217;s going through pale in comparison. He says, &#8220;They are alive. I am alive. That is what I am grateful for. That is all I can ask for.&#8221; </p>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F05%2F21%2Fthree-in-south-battle-flesh-eating-bacteria%2F&amp;title=Three%20in%20South%20Battle%20Flesh-Eating%20Bacteria" id="wpa2a_12"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/gwCm5v0pnMMnCMI2EWj6cWFcKNU/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/gwCm5v0pnMMnCMI2EWj6cWFcKNU/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/gwCm5v0pnMMnCMI2EWj6cWFcKNU/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/gwCm5v0pnMMnCMI2EWj6cWFcKNU/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:l6gmwiTKsz0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=l6gmwiTKsz0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:7Q72WNTAKBA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=7Q72WNTAKBA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:dnMXMwOfBR0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?d=dnMXMwOfBR0" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?a=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:-BTjWOF_DHI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/realscience/posts?i=FEpIVSMhBYM:1Fe0kT0XqlI:-BTjWOF_DHI" border="0"></img></a>
</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/realscience/posts/~4/FEpIVSMhBYM" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
