		<item>
		<title>SDF: Southern Belle Fights for her Life</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/odINZTy-yj4/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/18/sdf-southern-belle-fights-for-her-life/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 18 May 2012 19:33:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Biology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Diseases]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Health and Medicine]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Science Ditty Friday]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7120</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Editor’s Note: It&#8217;s Science Ditty Friday. Every Friday REALscience compiles a song (generally with an accompanying video) to kick your weekend off with a musical start. Have a favorite science song? Send it to ditty@realscience.us.

The news about Amimee Copeland is spreading like her flesh-eating bacteria. The sunny 24-year-old contracted a rare form of a common [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>Editor’s Note: It&#8217;s Science Ditty Friday. Every Friday REALscience compiles a song (generally with an accompanying video) to kick your weekend off with a musical start. Have a favorite science song? Send it to <strong><a href="mailto:ditty@realscience.us">ditty@realscience.us</a></strong></em>.</p>
<p><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/qBXZ-Vw4Hmg?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>The news about Amimee Copeland is spreading like her flesh-eating bacteria. The sunny 24-year-old contracted a rare form of a common bacteria after being injured on a zip-line at the beginning of the month. She has undergone several surgeries to have dead tissue removed, including amputation of her hands and feet.</p>
<p>The brave psychology grad student from Georgia appears to remain optimistic through her trials and tribulations. Her father says that she hasn&#8217;t shed a tear over the loss of her limbs and that she was bored in the hospital and requested a book. Doctors think those are good signs after giving the young woman low odds of even surviving the flesh-eating bacterial infection from exposure to <em>Aeromonas hydrophilia</em>.</p>
<p>This water-loving superbug is very common in untreated water supplies, including warm lakes and rivers, like the one Copeland landed in when a homemade zip-line broke. The gash she sustained on her leg required 22 stitches but was deep and bacteria made it&#8217;s way in and was sealed up by doctors where it was able to start eating tissue from the inside out.</p>
<p>When a bacteria gets into an open wound like Copeland&#8217;s it kills the healthy tissue, turning it black. The only way to treat the infection is to get ahead of it and remove the dead and dying flesh. The infection is incredibly painful and requires multiple surgeries until the doctors are convinced they have removed it all.</p>
<p>Every year about 800 people contract some form of flesh-eating bacteria, also known as necrotizing faciitis. One in five die from the infection. Most people who develop life-threatening cases have already compromised immune systems that prevent the body from fighting off the pathogen.</p>
<p>Copeland appeared to be the picture of health before she was injured and exposed to the waterborne bacteria. Some news reports say she was recently diagnosed with lupus. But her family denies that claim, saying that she was being tested for food allergies.</p>
<p>Students and faculty of the psychology department at the University of West Georgia have turned the website into an electronic newsletter, chronicling Copeland&#8217;s journey as she fights for her life.</p>
<p>Connecticut singer-songwriter <a href="http://coreydurkin.com/aimee-copeland">Corey Durkin</a> was so moved by Copeland&#8217;s story that he wrote a song for her.</p>
<blockquote><h3>Southern Belle</h3>
<p>By: Corey Durkin</p>
<p>I hope you know I hope you hear<br />
He&#8217;s got big plans for you<br />
I know you&#8217;re tired but we&#8217;re all here<br />
We&#8217;re gonna stand right by you</p>
<p>When your heart gets heavy and you wanna breathe<br />
And your eyes stop searching for the better season our love won&#8217;t go away<br />
No our love won&#8217;t go away<br />
When your hips start moving to a country song<br />
And your lips turn up as the morning comes our love</p>
<p>You&#8217;re just a southern belle<br />
Who fell down a wishing well<br />
And you&#8217;ve got time to give<br />
You&#8217;re more than a silhouette<br />
Asleep in a hospital bed<br />
And i don&#8217;t know anything about you<br />
But i want to</p>
<p>When you wake when you smile<br />
Now the whole world sees you<br />
Make your love take your time<br />
And your faith will guide you</p>
<p>When your heart gets heavy and you wanna breathe<br />
And your eyes stop searching for the better seasons our love won&#8217;t go away<br />
No our love won&#8217;t go away<br />
When your hips start moving to a country song<br />
And your lips turn up as the morning comes our love</p>
<p>You&#8217;re just a southern belle<br />
Who fell down a wishing well<br />
And you&#8217;ve got time to give<br />
You&#8217;re more than a silhouette<br />
Asleep in a hospital bed<br />
And i don&#8217;t know anything about you<br />
But i want to</p>
<p>Ride in the daylight with those heavy winds by your side<br />
I wanna see you as you are what you are is beautiful<br />
To watch you dance feeling so high with all your love and grace</p>
<p>Soon you&#8217;ll be back where you belong</p>
<p>You&#8217;re just a southern belle<br />
Who fell down a wishing well<br />
And you&#8217;ve got time to give<br />
You&#8217;re more than a silhouette<br />
Asleep in a hospital bed<br />
And i don&#8217;t know anything about you<br />
But i want to</p>
