		<item>
		<title>Young Explorer Circumnavigates the Americas</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/realscience/posts/~3/ULsknJi0Wj0/</link>
		<comments>http://www.realscience.us/2012/05/17/young-explorer-circumnavigates-the-americas/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 18 May 2012 00:52:19 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Michael Bradbury</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Around the Americas]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Climate Change]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[SciLebs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Video]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.realscience.us/?p=7082</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[
Matt Rutherford is not your typical 31 year old. The Annapolis, Maryland resident just returned from a 309-day sailing trip. The avid sailor becomes the first person to circumnavigate North and South America by himself. 
After traveling over 27,000 miles the young philanthropist returned to shore in Chesapeake Bay in late April, after completely a [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/6rSTY3uLf9A?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>Matt Rutherford is not your typical 31 year old. The Annapolis, Maryland resident just returned from a 309-day sailing trip. The avid sailor becomes the first person to circumnavigate North and South America by himself. <div id="attachment_7092" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 219px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford.jpg" alt="Matt Rutherford, First Man to Circumnavigate the Americas by Himself" title="MattRutherford" width="209" height="273" class="size-full wp-image-7092" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Matt Rutherford, First Man to Circumnavigate the Americas by Himself</p></div></p>
<p>After traveling over 27,000 miles the young philanthropist returned to shore in Chesapeake Bay in late April, after completely a trip that wasn&#8217;t even possible a few years ago. </p>
<p>Before setting out to accomplish this nautical feat, Rutherford didn&#8217;t plan much beyond sailing from east to west through the Northwest Passage, the no-longer-fabled sea route through the Canadian archipelago in the Arctic. After the ice began receding annually in August, Rutherford decided he wanted to be among the first to sail the passage.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7089" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford2.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford2-e1337386555521.jpg" alt="Rutherford Pilots the 27-Foot Albin Vega Sailboat, St. Brendan near Annapolis, Maryland after 309-Day Voyage" title="MattRutherford2" width="325" height="216" class="size-full wp-image-7089" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Rutherford Pilots the 27-Foot Albin Vega Sailboat, St. Brendan near Annapolis, Maryland after 309-Day Voyage</p></div>And if he and his 27-foot sloop made it through the treacherous waterway then he would continue the journey, setting his sights on the hair-raising milestone of Cape Horn at the southern tip of South America. Eventually, he hit all his goals and successfully sailed around both continents.</p>
<p>But first he had to sail through the Arctic.</p>
<p>Before leaving Annapolis last June Rutherford was focused on the Northwest Passage. Then, he said, &#8220;The ice won’t melt enough to make the attempt until August.&#8221; </p>
<p>And it did. He describes the journey across the far north as hairy, getting locked into long foggy stretches of flat water with floating iceberg obstacles.</p>
<p>But the Northwest Passage afforded him his favorite moment &#8212; spotting narwhals &#8212; which now inspires him to return there to film a documentary (his next project.)</p>
<p>He did almost get run over by a freighter in the home stretch. His engine died 7,000 miles from home. And he had a few scary days in the Arctic. </p>
<p>Rutherford&#8217;s Albin-Vega sailboat doesn&#8217;t have radar so sailing at night or in fog can be dangerous. When he reached Baffin Bay in the southern Arctic last July the fog rolled in for a few sleepless days. Then, he said, &#8220;I never have been a fan of the fog but when you are sailing blindly, surrounded by icebergs with no radar, things get a bit dodgy.&#8221; <div id="attachment_7091" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordIcebergNWPassage.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordIcebergNWPassage-e1337386638243.jpg" alt="Iceberg Cathedral at 75.22.410n, the Northern Point of the Solo the Americas Voyage, photo by Matt Rutherford" title="MattRutherfordIcebergNWPassage" width="325" height="193" class="size-full wp-image-7091" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Iceberg Cathedral at 75.22.410n, the Northern Point of the Solo the Americas Voyage, photo by Matt Rutherford</p></div></p>
<p>He says the fog dissipated and he found himself surrounded by five large icebergs within a mile of his position. The sun came out but the wind died so he crawled through parts of the passage where temperatures were a balmy 60 degrees last summer. This is an area that used to be ice-locked year round. But since 2007 the Northwest Passage has opened for several weeks during the late summer, allowing dozens of vessels to cross the top of North America.</p>
<p>Rutherford says that the area is still not ice-free but it is ice-less, meaning that boats can sail around icebergs of all sizes and shapes. He says, &#8220;I can deal with ice bergs but pack ice is something very different. Speaking of ice bergs I’ve seen more then I can count. From giant growlers the size of a large office building to bergy bits the size of a VW bug.&#8221;</p>
<p>He thinks it&#8217;s worth sailing to the Northwest Passage just to see the icebergs. He says, &#8220;The bergs are natures sculptures, each one unique and as they melt and break apart their beauty changes and evolves. Some are bleach white but most have a tint of blue or sometimes pink.&#8221;</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7097" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford3.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherford3-e1337388348230.jpg" alt="Matt Rutherford Sailing the Northwest Passage, photo by Matt Rutherford" title="MattRutherford3" width="325" height="244" class="size-full wp-image-7097" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Matt Rutherford Sailing the Northwest Passage, photo by Matt Rutherford</p></div>While hugging the northwest coast of Greenland he didn&#8217;t sleep for three days and lamented not having a crew to watch for icebergs. He says, &#8220;I didn’t sleep for 3 days and only got a couple hours sleep last night broken up in 20 minute intervals. Because the sun never sets up here my concept of time has been destroyed.&#8221;</p>
<p>But that makes sailing through bergy water a little easier, providing the fog doesn&#8217;t shut down visibility.</p>
<p>Rutherford says, &#8220;Icebergs are amazingly beautifully, but man is it hard to sleep when they’re around. Hitting a berg would be like running into a giant rock. The ice has no forgiveness and would sink my little boat in record time.&#8221;</p>
<p>By the time he entered the Northwest Passage proper temperatures dropped to the 30s and the ice was still choking the narrow passage. He arrived on Day 50 of his journey, tired, wet and rattled.</p>
<p>After fighting a diesel leak he almost hit a mammoth iceberg, sailed for a straight 50 hours without sleep all while trying to discern whitecaps kicked up by 30-knot winds from low-lying iceberg tips.</p>
<p>He says, &#8220;With all the drama aside – Baffin Bay is one of my favorite places I’ve ever sailed. It’s up there with the Gambia river, Galicia, and the Exumas. Between the icebergs of unexplainable beauty and 24 hours of daylight it’s as unique as any body of water can be. I’m happy to trade sleep for a chance to sail such incredible waters, but it’s also the most dangerous place I’ve ever sailed. It’s a place I love, fear and respect.&#8221;</p>
<p>From 2008 to 2010 Rutherford sailed the North Atlantic across to Europe, through Northern Europe, down the coast of Africa, and ultimately 200 miles up the Gambia River before returning via the Trade Wind route to the Caribbean.</p>
<p>With his previous sailing adventures firmly in mind, Rutherford continued his journey west, toward Alaska.</p>
<p>He fought sleep depravation, fog and the constant concern of crashing into an iceberg by singing to himself for hours. He says, &#8220;I usally start off with some Wu-Tang but its not long until I’m singing Christmas carols. That probably sounds strange considering its the middle of the summer, but you couldn’t tell me that – I’m surrounded by ice. Plus, Santa only lives two blocks down the road.&#8221;</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7093" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 257px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordCrokerBayIceberg.png"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordCrokerBayIceberg.png" alt="Icebergs in Croker Bay, photo by Matt Rutherford" title="MattRutherfordCrokerBayIceberg" width="247" height="186" class="size-full wp-image-7093" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Icebergs in Croker Bay, photo by Matt Rutherford</p></div>In Croker Bay Rutherford caught up on repairs and sleep, floating in a quiet bay amid a curious flotilla of icebergs, ranging from the size of a shopping cart to a house, with many about the size of a semi-truck. He fended off a few icy interlopers with his boat hook, and even caught some ice with his fishing net. He melted the fresh ice with a pot mounted on his engine and even treated himself to a Scotch on the rocks, where he says, &#8220;The rocks coming strait off a glacier and had been frozen for a millennia. Now thats a good drink!&#8221;</p>
<p>Even though the Northwest Passage is open for part of the summer every year after thousands of years of being iced in sailors have to time their passage carefully, following the shifting ice and making a run based on recommendations from Canadian officials who monitor the area. </p>
<p>By the second week of August Rutherford reached a point in the passage where the ice was about 50 percent open at the top but only 5 percent at the bottom. As the ice shifted, pushed by steady winds, he made his run through Peel Sound, hoping to reach the western entrance before the ice closed back in.</p>
<p>To make his circumnavigation a non-stop trip Rutherford&#8217;s boat, St. Brendan (named for the Irish saint who sailed across the North Atlantic in search of the Garden of Eden) couldn&#8217;t dock, anchor or tie up to anything attached to the ground. He could tie up to a floating iceberg or use his parachute sea anchor (which doesn&#8217;t attach to anything) to be considered a vessel under way, according to U.S. Coast Guard guidelines.</p>
<p>He says, &#8220;The reason for the non-stop part of the trip is simple – for some time I’ve wanted to sail alone around the world non-stop in the southern latitudes. I’ve also wanted to sail the Northwest Passage. So I combined the two and this way I can sail both the Northwest Passage and Cape Horn.&#8221; <div id="attachment_7087" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 335px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordmap.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MattRutherfordmap-e1337387915589.jpg" alt="Matt Rutherford&#039;s Solo Navigation Route around North and South America" title="MattRutherfordmap" width="325" height="553" class="size-full wp-image-7087" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Matt Rutherford&#039;s Solo Navigation Route around North and South America</p></div></p>
<p>Halfway down Peel Sound, Rutherford ran into a marine party, which he describes as a stretch of water filled with seals, seabirds and narwhals (tusked whales). He says he was afraid to fish in the area for fear of hooking a seal. But says the narwhals were a trip highlight. he says, &#8220;The narwhals didn’t seem to pay any attention to my boat, they would swim right by like they had no care in the world. I must of seen at least 50 of them, it went on like this for miles. I can believe I’ve actually seen a narwhal!&#8221;</p>
<p>In mid-August Rutherford says that temperatures were still hovering around 60 degrees, which he says was great for him but terrible for the Arctic.</p>
<p>He says, &#8220;I have a bad feeling that if things stay this way the Arctic is going to be decimated in the next 15 years or so and its going to effect us all.&#8221;</p>
<p>When he reached the halfway point of the Northwest Passage Rutherford ran into a series of strong storms which kept his boat wet most of the time. He noted that much of the wood on the boat was turning black from wood rot and his books and other belongings were collecting black mold.</p>
<p>By the time he reached the western side of the passage he was being regularly battered by strong wind and rain, part of which was a leftover typhoon from Asia that made sailing difficult.</p>
<p>But on September 19, a triumphant yet soggy Rutherford finished his journey across the top of North America. <a href="http://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/">Scott Polar Research Institute</a> recorded his passage as the the smallest single-handed boat in history to make it through the Northwest passage.</p>
<p>Rutherford postulates that he set another record. He says, &#8220;I imagine I’ve also sailed the cheapest boat in history threw the Northwest Passage as ST Brendan is only worth around ten grand.&#8221;</p>
<p>After making the harrowing trip around the Americas a modest Rutherford tells <a href="http://www.sail-world.com/cruising/canada/Matt-Rutherford-solo-around-the-Americas:-Exclusive-interview/97114">Sail World</a>, &#8220;The ocean can be difficult but for the most part my circumnavigation of the Americas was a pleasant and enjoyable experience.&#8221;</p>
<p>But others describe Rutherford&#8217;s feat in terms of other great explorers.</p>
<p>Lee Tawney, director of the National Sailing Hall of Fame compared him to Sir Edmund Hillary and says it is like Rutherford scaled Mount Everest without Sherpas. </p>
<p>Rutherford&#8217;s friend Andy Shell says that the single-hander (solo sailor in sailing speak) belongs in the group that make up the Mount Rushmore of sailing pioneers.</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7090" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 247px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CRABlogo.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CRABlogo.jpg" alt="Chesapeake Region Accessible Boating, Rutherford&#039;s Charity" title="CRABlogo" width="237" height="106" class="size-full wp-image-7090" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Chesapeake Region Accessible Boating, Rutherford&#039;s Charity</p></div>His journey wasn&#8217;t just one of vanity. Rutherford was raising money for <a href="http://crabsailing.org/">Chesapeake Regional Assessable Boating</a> (CRAB). The Annapolis-based charity has been helping mentally and physically disabled people learn to sail for over 20 years. He set a goal to raise $250,000 for the organization where he has volunteered. By the time he reached land on April 21, he had raised over $80,000.</p>
<p>While on a boat delivery from Chesapeake Bay to the Caribbean island of Antigua Rutherford shared his idea to start a sailing non-profit organization for disabled people with fellow sailor Tag Hunt. That&#8217;s when he first learned of CRAB. When he returned from that trip he met with CRAB founder Don Backe. After volunteering there for a few months, Rutherford joked that Backe should let him sail a 25-foot folkboat the charity had for sale through the Northwest Passage. <div id="attachment_7094" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 270px"><a href="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DonBacke.jpg"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DonBacke-e1337387486305.jpg" alt="Don Backe, Co-Founder of CRAB" title="DonBacke" width="260" height="228" class="size-full wp-image-7094" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Don Backe, Co-Founder of CRAB</p></div></p>
<p>He says, &#8220;I said to Don &#8216;You should let me take that boat up to the Northwest Passage and we&#8217;ll raise some money for CRAB.&#8217;&#8221; Instead of laughing at Rutherford, Backe backed the idea and the <a href="http://www.solotheamericas.org/">Solo the Americas</a> journey was born. The website says, &#8220;Matt&#8217;s motivation for the trip is to show people, particularly those with disabilities, that there are no limits to what can be accomplished in life; and to raise money for Chesapeake Region Accessible Boating.&#8221;</p>
<p>Rutherford is inspired by Backe&#8217;s unflinching optimism. After a severe car accident 25 years ago left Backe paralyzed, he co-founded CRAB. After the accident Rutherford says, &#8220;He was able to move on with his life without being depressed and saying &#8216;woe is me.&#8217;&#8221;</p>
<p>As Rutherford was making his final push for Annapolis in April, the crew of the boat Godspeed (the one Rutherford was sailing to Antigua when he first heard of CRAB) decided to match all donations (up to $21,000) made to CRAB through the end of May.</p>
<p>When it comes to sailing many agree that it&#8217;s very difficult to say who did what when because so many people have sailed so many places. Rutherford says his trip is much easier to track because of the Northwest Passage element. Few boats have sailed through the Northwest Passage and every boat that has is listed on the Scott Polar Research Institute&#8217;s website at University of Cambridge along with the number of crew. </p>
<p>Out of these boats very few were sailed through the Northwest Passage single-handed and out of those few only a couple boats did it both single-handed and non-stop. Rutherford says, &#8220;The very very few that have did not continue non-stop to Cape Horn and then back to their original starting point. So – long story short I’m the first person in history to have completed a non-stop single-handed circumnavigation of the Americas.&#8221; </p>
<p>Total mileage: 27,700<br />
Total time: 309 Days 18 Hours and 5 Minutes (only 5 hours off of his predicted 310-day estimate)</p>
<p>Next Trip: </p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;The next trip (if I can raise the money) will be a trip back up to the artic. The idea is to have a few crew, one of which is a friend of mine who is a polar scientist. He will bring scientific instruments and we will sail to the extreme northern regions of the Northwest Passage and collect scientific data in places scientists usually don’t get to go. So it will not just be a trip to the arctic, it will be a scientific expedition. We will also shoot a documentary and raise money for a non-profit. So all in all I’m trying to sail back to the arctic on a scientific expedition and shoot a documentary that focuses on climate change and raise some money for charity. Sounds like a good idea to me.&#8221; &#8211;Matt Rutherford, May 11, 2012</p></blockquote>
<p><a class="a2a_dd a2a_target addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.realscience.us%2F2012%2F05%2F17%2Fyoung-explorer-circumnavigates-the-americas%2F&amp;title=Young%20Explorer%20Circumnavigates%20the%20Americas" id="wpa2a_16"><img src="http://www.realscience.us/blog/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/share_save_256_24.png" width="256" height="24" alt="Share"/></a></p>
